    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:83dd89b4-9776-41fe-92b8-60b21f175453",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 11-year-old girl who presents to the pediatric outpatient clinic accompanied by her mother and younger brother. She is a slender child of average height for her age, with dark brown hair pulled into an uneven ponytail, restless fingers that tap continuously on the edge of the exam table, and bright, darting eyes that sweep the room rather than maintaining eye contact. She is dressed in a slightly mismatched outfit — her shirt is inside-out — and she carries a well-worn sketchbook filled with doodles of horses and cartoon figures.\n\n{patientName} is in the fifth grade at a public elementary school, where she has always been described by teachers as \"bright but scattered.\" She loves art class and gym but struggles enormously with sitting still during reading and math, frequently losing her worksheets and forgetting homework assignments despite multiple reminders. Her mother reports that {patientName} often starts several tasks simultaneously — getting dressed, feeding the cat, packing her school bag — and completes none of them without prompting. She will hyperfocus for hours on her sketchbook or watching nature documentaries, yet cannot sustain attention during structured academic work for more than five minutes.\n\nAt home, {patientName} shares a bedroom with her younger brother and often keeps the whole family awake with her restless nighttime activity. She has difficulty falling asleep, frequently getting out of bed to reorganize her art supplies or flip through books. Her appetite is modest; her mother notes she sometimes forgets to eat lunch entirely. She has a close-knit group of two or three friends who share her love of drawing and animals, but she often interrupts conversations and can become frustrated when she feels misunderstood, occasionally leading to minor conflicts at school.\n\n{patientName} participates in an after-school horse-riding program once a week, which her mother says is one of the few activities that reliably calms and focuses her. She has never been formally diagnosed before this visit, though teachers flagged concerns as early as second grade. Her mother finally sought evaluation after {patientName}'s most recent report card showed declining grades despite evident intelligence and effort."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2e26b5b5-be12-4abd-beae-459b2938c627",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at 39 weeks via uncomplicated vaginal delivery with no perinatal complications and achieved all early developmental milestones within normal limits, though her mother notes she was an unusually active toddler who rarely napped. She has no history of epilepsy, head trauma, or prior psychiatric hospitalizations. She had a single episode of otitis media at age 5 treated with antibiotics. There is no history of substance use.\n\n{patientName} has no known chronic medical conditions other than the current presentation. She does not take any regular medications prior to this visit. Sleep-onset difficulties have been present since early childhood. Her diet is unremarkable, though appetite is somewhat reduced in the afternoon and evening. She is up to date on all vaccinations. She has never undergone formal neuropsychological testing prior to this evaluation, though informal teacher observations have been consistent over multiple school years. There is a significant family history of ADHD in her father. Her BMI is within the normal range for age. Physical examination is unremarkable, and no focal neurological deficits are detected."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}